75","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","abt 1275":"about 1275","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1313":"1313","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","16 Feb 1312":"16 February 1312","1332":"1332","1221":"1221","Brabant Flamand, Belgium":"Flemish Brabant, Belgium","France":"France","of Brabant, Flanders, France":"Brabant-en-Argonne, Meuse, Lorraine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jean Ier de Barbançon was born in France as the son of Nicolas II de Barbençon and Isabeau ou Isabelle de Soissons de Nesle. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Marie d'Antoing. He died on 16 February 1312."},"et":{"–16 Feb 1312":"–16. veebruar 1312","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1251–1313":"1251–1313","–1312":"–1312","1257–Female":"1257–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1280–1325":"1280–1325","1282–1332":"1282–1332","–Female":"Surnud","1215–1256":"1215–1256","1224–1250":"1224–1250","1275":"1275","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","abt 1275":"umbes 1275","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1313":"1313","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","16 Feb 1312":"16. veebruar 1312","1332":"1332","1221":"1221","Brabant Flamand, Belgium":"Vlaams-Brabant, Belgia","France":"Prantsusmaa","of Brabant, Flanders, France":"Brabant-en-Ar